-- LESSON: lesson-t-pointers
-- Images mapped to sections:
-- page8_img1 -> "Passing by Value vs Pointer"
-- page8_img2 -> "Pointers and Arrays"
-- page9_img1 -> "Pointers to Structures"
-- page9_img2 -> "C++ References"
-- page10_img1 -> "Const Pointers"
-- page11_img1 -> "Pointers in Interrupts and Tasks"
-- ============================================================================
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = json_set(
  json_remove(content_json, '$.images'),
  '$.sections',
  json('[
    {"title":"Introduction to Pointers and References","content":"Pointers and references are fundamental to embedded systems programming. They enable efficient memory usage, direct hardware access, and passing data between functions without copying.\n\nIn embedded systems, you will use pointers to:\n- Access hardware registers at specific memory addresses\n- Pass large data structures efficiently\n- Share data between interrupt handlers and main code\n- Work with arrays and buffers"},
    {"title":"Pointer Basics","content":"A pointer is a variable that stores a memory address. The address-of operator `&` gets a variable''s address, and the dereference operator `*` accesses the value at that address.\n\n```c\nint value = 42;\nint *ptr = &value;    // ptr holds address of value\n*ptr = 100;           // changes value to 100\n```\n\nUnderstanding pointer syntax is critical for embedded development where direct memory manipulation is common."},
    {"title":"Passing by Value vs Pointer","content":"When you pass a variable by value, the function receives a copy. Changes to the copy do not affect the original.\n\nWhen you pass a pointer, the function can modify the original variable through the pointer.\n\n```c\n// Pass by value - cannot modify original\nvoid set_value(int x) {\n    x = 100;  // Only changes local copy\n}\n\n// Pass by pointer - can modify original\nvoid set_value_ptr(int *x) {\n    *x = 100;  // Changes original variable\n}\n\nint main() {\n    int a = 0;\n    set_value(a);      // a is still 0\n    set_value_ptr(&a); // a is now 100\n}\n```\n\nIn embedded systems, passing by pointer is essential for efficiency and for functions that need to return multiple values.","images":[{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/OyaALdF5","alt":"Pass by value vs pointer comparison","caption":"Pass by Value vs Pass by Pointer"}]},
    {"title":"Pointers and Arrays","content":"Arrays and pointers are closely related in C. An array name decays to a pointer to its first element when passed to a function.\n\n```c\nvoid process_buffer(uint8_t *data, int length) {\n    for (int i = 0; i < length; i++) {\n        data[i] = data[i] * 2;\n    }\n}\n\nint main() {\n    uint8_t buffer[10] = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};\n    process_buffer(buffer, 10);  // buffer decays to pointer\n}\n```\n\nThis is why functions receiving arrays typically also need a length parameter - the pointer alone does not carry size information.","images":[{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/p8A1J3Lm","alt":"Array passed as pointer","caption":"Arrays Decay to Pointers"}]},
    {"title":"Pointers to Structures","content":"Structures are often passed by pointer to avoid copying large amounts of data. The arrow operator `->` is used to access members through a pointer.\n\n```c\ntypedef struct {\n    int16_t x;\n    int16_t y;\n    int16_t z;\n} AccelData;\n\nvoid read_accelerometer(AccelData *data) {\n    data->x = i2c_read_reg(ACCEL_ADDR, X_REG);\n    data->y = i2c_read_reg(ACCEL_ADDR, Y_REG);\n    data->z = i2c_read_reg(ACCEL_ADDR, Z_REG);\n}\n\nint main() {\n    AccelData accel;\n    read_accelerometer(&accel);\n}\n```\n\nPassing structures by pointer is standard practice in embedded code for both efficiency and to allow functions to populate data.","images":[{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/gLkYh9Wv","alt":"Pointer to structure example","caption":"Passing Structures by Pointer"}]},
    {"title":"C++ References","content":"C++ references provide an alternative to pointers with cleaner syntax. A reference is an alias for another variable.\n\n```cpp\nvoid set_value(int &x) {\n    x = 100;  // Modifies original directly\n}\n\nint main() {\n    int a = 0;\n    set_value(a);  // a is now 100\n}\n```\n\nReferences cannot be null and cannot be reassigned, making them safer than pointers in many situations. However, pointers are still needed for dynamic memory and hardware addresses.","images":[{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/Q7mNpRsT","alt":"C++ reference example","caption":"C++ References"}]},
    {"title":"Const Pointers","content":"The `const` keyword with pointers prevents accidental modification. There are two variations:\n\n```c\n// Pointer to const data - cannot modify data through pointer\nvoid print_buffer(const uint8_t *data, int len) {\n    // data[0] = 0;  // ERROR: cannot modify\n    for (int i = 0; i < len; i++) {\n        printf(\"%d \", data[i]);\n    }\n}\n\n// Const pointer - cannot change what pointer points to\nuint8_t * const fixed_ptr = buffer;\n// fixed_ptr = other;  // ERROR: cannot reassign pointer\n```\n\nUsing `const` correctly helps catch bugs at compile time and documents function intent.","images":[{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/jH4kLmNp","alt":"Const pointer in function signature","caption":"Const Pointers for Safety"}]},
    {"title":"Pointers in Interrupts and Tasks","content":"When sharing data between interrupt handlers and main code, or between RTOS tasks, pointers often reference `volatile` variables.\n\n```c\nvolatile uint8_t button_pressed = 0;\n\nvoid IRAM_ATTR button_isr() {\n    button_pressed = 1;\n}\n\nvoid main_loop() {\n    if (button_pressed) {\n        button_pressed = 0;\n        handle_button();\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThe `volatile` keyword tells the compiler the variable can change unexpectedly, preventing optimizations that would cause incorrect behavior.","images":[{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/rS5tUvWx","alt":"Volatile variable for ISR","caption":"Volatile Variables in Interrupts"}]}
  ]')
) WHERE id = 'lesson-t-pointers';

-- ============================================================================
-- LESSON: lesson-t-bits
-- Images mapped to sections:
-- page13_img1 -> "Masking to Extract Bits"
-- page14_img1 -> "Setting a Bit"
-- page14_img2 -> "Clearing a Bit"
-- page15_img1 -> "Toggling a Bit"
-- page15_img2 -> "Bit Field Manipulation"
-- page15_img3 -> "Combining and Extracting Nibbles" (combining)
-- page15_img4 -> "Combining and Extracting Nibbles" (extracting)
-- ============================================================================
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = json_set(
  json_remove(content_json, '$.images'),
  '$.sections',
  json('[
    {"title":"Why Bit Manipulation Matters","content":"In embedded systems, you frequently work at the bit level. Hardware registers, communication protocols, and sensor data often pack multiple values into single bytes or words.\n\nBit manipulation allows you to:\n- Read and write individual hardware register bits\n- Extract fields from packed data structures\n- Efficiently store boolean flags\n- Implement communication protocols\n\nMastering bitwise operations is essential for embedded firmware development."},
    {"title":"Bitwise Operators","content":"C provides six bitwise operators for manipulating individual bits:\n\n| Operator | Name | Description |\n|----------|------|-------------|\n| `&` | AND | 1 if both bits are 1 |\n| `\\|` | OR | 1 if either bit is 1 |\n| `^` | XOR | 1 if bits are different |\n| `~` | NOT | Inverts all bits |\n| `<<` | Left Shift | Shifts bits left |\n| `>>` | Right Shift | Shifts bits right |\n\n```c\nuint8_t a = 0b11001010;\nuint8_t b = 0b10101100;\n\na & b;   // 0b10001000 (AND)\na | b;   // 0b11101110 (OR)\na ^ b;   // 0b01100110 (XOR)\n~a;      // 0b00110101 (NOT)\na << 2;  // 0b00101000 (Left shift by 2)\na >> 2;  // 0b00110010 (Right shift by 2)\n```"},
    {"title":"Masking to Extract Bits","content":"A mask is a bit pattern used to isolate specific bits. AND with a mask extracts those bits, setting all others to zero.\n\n```c\n// Extract the lower nibble (bits 0-3)\nuint8_t value = 0x5A;  // 0101 1010\nuint8_t lower = value & 0x0F;  // 0000 1010 = 0x0A\n\n// Extract bits 4-6\nuint8_t bits_4_6 = (value >> 4) & 0x07;  // Shift then mask\n```\n\nMasking is commonly used to read BCD (Binary Coded Decimal) data from RTC chips and extract fields from sensor registers.","images":[{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/yZ6aBcDe","alt":"BCD masking example","caption":"Masking to Extract Bits from BCD Data"}]},
    {"title":"Setting a Bit","content":"To set (turn on) a specific bit, OR with a mask that has 1 in that position.\n\n```c\n// Set bit 3 (counting from 0)\nuint8_t reg = 0b00000000;\nreg = reg | (1 << 3);  // 0b00001000\n\n// Shorthand\nreg |= (1 << 3);\n\n// Set multiple bits\nreg |= (1 << 5) | (1 << 2);  // Set bits 5 and 2\n```\n\nSetting bits is used to enable features in hardware registers or set flags in status variables.","images":[{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/fG7hIjKl","alt":"Setting bit 3 example","caption":"Setting a Bit with OR"}]},
    {"title":"Clearing a Bit","content":"To clear (turn off) a specific bit, AND with a mask that has 0 in that position and 1s elsewhere.\n\n```c\n// Clear bit 2\nuint8_t reg = 0b11111111;\nreg = reg & ~(1 << 2);  // 0b11111011\n\n// Shorthand\nreg &= ~(1 << 2);\n\n// Clear multiple bits\nreg &= ~((1 << 5) | (1 << 2));  // Clear bits 5 and 2\n```\n\nClearing bits disables features or acknowledges interrupts in hardware registers.","images":[{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/mN8oPqRs","alt":"Clearing bit 2 example","caption":"Clearing a Bit with AND NOT"}]},
    {"title":"Toggling a Bit","content":"To toggle (flip) a specific bit, XOR with a mask that has 1 in that position.\n\n```c\n// Toggle bit 4\nuint8_t reg = 0b00010000;\nreg = reg ^ (1 << 4);  // 0b00000000\nreg = reg ^ (1 << 4);  // 0b00010000 (back to original)\n\n// Shorthand\nreg ^= (1 << 4);\n```\n\nToggling is useful for blinking LEDs or alternating between two states.","images":[{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/tU9vWxYz","alt":"Toggling a bit example","caption":"Toggling a Bit with XOR"}]},
    {"title":"Bit Field Manipulation","content":"A bit field is a group of adjacent bits that represent a single value. To modify a bit field, first clear it, then set the new value.\n\n```c\n// Bits 4-6 form a 3-bit field (values 0-7)\nuint8_t reg = 0b01110011;  // Field currently = 7\n\n// Clear the field (bits 4-6)\nreg &= ~(0x07 << 4);  // 0b00000011\n\n// Set new value (3) in the field\nreg |= (3 << 4);  // 0b00110011\n\n// Combined: clear and set in one step\nreg = (reg & ~(0x07 << 4)) | (new_value << 4);\n```\n\nBit fields are common in hardware configuration registers where different settings occupy different bit ranges.","images":[{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/aB1cDeFg","alt":"Bit field manipulation","caption":"Clearing and Inserting a Bit Field"}]},
    {"title":"Combining and Extracting Nibbles","content":"A nibble is 4 bits (half a byte). Many protocols and formats pack two values into a single byte.\n\n```c\n// Combine two nibbles into one byte\nuint8_t high_nibble = 0x0A;  // 1010\nuint8_t low_nibble = 0x05;   // 0101\nuint8_t combined = (high_nibble << 4) | low_nibble;  // 0xA5\n\n// Extract nibbles from a byte\nuint8_t value = 0xA5;\nuint8_t high = (value >> 4) & 0x0F;  // 0x0A\nuint8_t low = value & 0x0F;          // 0x05\n```\n\nBCD (Binary Coded Decimal) data from RTC chips uses this format, storing tens digit in the upper nibble and ones digit in the lower nibble.","images":[{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/hI2jKlMn","alt":"Combining nibbles","caption":"Combining Two Nibbles"},{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/oP3qRsTu","alt":"Extracting nibbles","caption":"Extracting Nibbles from a Byte"}]}
  ]')
) WHERE id = 'lesson-t-bits';

-- ============================================================================
-- LESSON: lesson-t-i2c
-- Images mapped to sections:
-- page17_img1 -> "I2C Pin Configuration"
-- page18_img1 -> "I2C Initialization"
-- page19_img1 -> "Read and Write Functions"
-- ALSO: Add missing video URL
-- ============================================================================
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = json_set(
  json_remove(content_json, '$.images'),
  '$.video_url', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CAvawEcxoPU',
  '$.sections',
  json('[
    {"title":"Introduction to I2C","content":"I2C (Inter-Integrated Circuit) is a synchronous serial communication protocol widely used in embedded systems. It uses two wires:\n\n- **SDA** (Serial Data) - Bidirectional data line\n- **SCL** (Serial Clock) - Clock signal from master\n\nI2C supports multiple devices on the same bus, each with a unique 7-bit address. The T-Watch uses I2C to communicate with the accelerometer (BMA423), power management IC (AXP202), and real-time clock (PCF8563)."},
    {"title":"I2C Pin Configuration","content":"Before using I2C, you must define the pins and device addresses. On the T-Watch, I2C uses GPIO21 (SDA) and GPIO22 (SCL).\n\n```c\n#define I2C_SDA_PIN     21\n#define I2C_SCL_PIN     22\n#define I2C_FREQUENCY   400000  // 400kHz Fast Mode\n\n// Device addresses\n#define AXP202_ADDR     0x35\n#define PCF8563_ADDR    0x51\n#define BMA423_ADDR     0x18\n```\n\nAlways verify pin assignments and addresses against the hardware schematic and datasheets.","images":[{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/vW4xYzAb","alt":"I2C configuration defines","caption":"I2C Pin and Address Configuration"}]},
    {"title":"I2C Initialization","content":"Initialize the I2C peripheral before communicating with devices. The ESP32 Arduino framework uses the Wire library.\n\n```cpp\n#include <Wire.h>\n\nvoid i2c_init(void) {\n    Wire.begin(I2C_SDA_PIN, I2C_SCL_PIN, I2C_FREQUENCY);\n}\n```\n\nFor low-level control, you can use the ESP-IDF I2C driver:\n\n```c\ni2c_config_t conf = {\n    .mode = I2C_MODE_MASTER,\n    .sda_io_num = I2C_SDA_PIN,\n    .scl_io_num = I2C_SCL_PIN,\n    .sda_pullup_en = GPIO_PULLUP_ENABLE,\n    .scl_pullup_en = GPIO_PULLUP_ENABLE,\n    .master.clk_speed = I2C_FREQUENCY\n};\ni2c_param_config(I2C_NUM_0, &conf);\ni2c_driver_install(I2C_NUM_0, I2C_MODE_MASTER, 0, 0, 0);\n```","images":[{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/cD5eFgHi","alt":"I2C initialization code","caption":"I2C Master Initialization"}]},
    {"title":"Driver Architecture","content":"A well-designed I2C driver separates low-level communication from device-specific logic:\n\n**Low-level functions:**\n- `i2c_write_reg()` - Write a value to a register\n- `i2c_read_reg()` - Read a value from a register\n- `i2c_read_bytes()` - Read multiple bytes\n\n**Device-specific functions:**\n- `accel_init()`, `accel_read_xyz()`\n- `rtc_get_time()`, `rtc_set_time()`\n- `pmu_get_battery()`, `pmu_enable_output()`\n\nThis separation makes code reusable and easier to maintain."},
    {"title":"Read and Write Functions","content":"Generic I2C read/write functions form the foundation of your driver:\n\n```c\nbool i2c_write_reg(uint8_t addr, uint8_t reg, uint8_t value) {\n    Wire.beginTransmission(addr);\n    Wire.write(reg);\n    Wire.write(value);\n    return Wire.endTransmission() == 0;\n}\n\nuint8_t i2c_read_reg(uint8_t addr, uint8_t reg) {\n    Wire.beginTransmission(addr);\n    Wire.write(reg);\n    Wire.endTransmission(false);  // Repeated start\n    Wire.requestFrom(addr, (uint8_t)1);\n    return Wire.read();\n}\n\nbool i2c_read_bytes(uint8_t addr, uint8_t reg, uint8_t *data, uint8_t len) {\n    Wire.beginTransmission(addr);\n    Wire.write(reg);\n    Wire.endTransmission(false);\n    Wire.requestFrom(addr, len);\n    for (int i = 0; i < len && Wire.available(); i++) {\n        data[i] = Wire.read();\n    }\n    return true;\n}\n```","images":[{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/jK6lMnOp","alt":"I2C read write functions","caption":"I2C Driver Read/Write Functions"}]},
    {"title":"Device-Specific Functions","content":"Build device-specific functions on top of the generic I2C layer:\n\n```c\n// RTC: Read current time\nvoid rtc_get_time(uint8_t *hour, uint8_t *min, uint8_t *sec) {\n    uint8_t data[3];\n    i2c_read_bytes(PCF8563_ADDR, 0x02, data, 3);\n    *sec = bcd_to_dec(data[0] & 0x7F);\n    *min = bcd_to_dec(data[1] & 0x7F);\n    *hour = bcd_to_dec(data[2] & 0x3F);\n}\n\n// Accelerometer: Read XYZ\nvoid accel_read_xyz(int16_t *x, int16_t *y, int16_t *z) {\n    uint8_t data[6];\n    i2c_read_bytes(BMA423_ADDR, 0x12, data, 6);\n    *x = (int16_t)((data[1] << 8) | data[0]) >> 4;\n    *y = (int16_t)((data[3] << 8) | data[2]) >> 4;\n    *z = (int16_t)((data[5] << 8) | data[4]) >> 4;\n}\n```\n\nRefer to device datasheets for register addresses and data formats."},
    {"title":"Error Handling","content":"Always check for communication errors and implement appropriate recovery:\n\n```c\nbool i2c_write_reg_safe(uint8_t addr, uint8_t reg, uint8_t value) {\n    for (int retry = 0; retry < 3; retry++) {\n        if (i2c_write_reg(addr, reg, value)) {\n            return true;\n        }\n        delay(1);  // Brief delay before retry\n    }\n    Serial.printf(\"I2C write failed: addr=0x%02X reg=0x%02X\\n\", addr, reg);\n    return false;\n}\n```\n\nCommon I2C issues include:\n- Wrong device address\n- Device not powered or in sleep mode\n- Bus contention from multiple masters\n- Missing pull-up resistors"}
  ]')
) WHERE id = 'lesson-t-i2c';

