-- LESSON: lesson-t-rtos
-- Images mapped to sections:
-- page27_img1 -> "Tasks" (Task Function Structure)
-- page27_img2 -> "Creating Tasks"
-- page28_img1 -> "Mutexes for Shared Resources" (Using Mutex in a Task)
-- page29_img1 -> "Mutexes for Shared Resources" (Mutex Task Display Example) - MISSING, adding now
-- page29_img2 -> "Multiple Tasks with Mutex"
-- ============================================================================
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = json_set(
  json_remove(content_json, '$.images'),
  '$.sections',
  json('[
    {"title":"Introduction to RTOS","content":"A Real-Time Operating System (RTOS) enables concurrent execution of multiple tasks. FreeRTOS, which runs on the ESP32, provides:\n\n- **Task scheduling** - Multiple functions run \"simultaneously\"\n- **Synchronization** - Mutexes, semaphores, queues\n- **Timing** - Precise delays and timeouts\n- **Memory management** - Dynamic allocation for tasks\n\nThe T-Watch uses FreeRTOS to handle display updates, sensor reading, and user input concurrently."},
    {"title":"Tasks","content":"A task is a function that runs independently. Each task has its own stack and runs in an infinite loop.\n\n```c\nvoid sensorTask(void *parameter) {\n    while (1) {\n        // Read sensor data\n        int16_t x = accel_read_x();\n        int16_t y = accel_read_y();\n        \n        // Process data\n        update_step_count(x, y);\n        \n        // Delay before next iteration\n        vTaskDelay(pdMS_TO_TICKS(100));\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThe `vTaskDelay()` function yields CPU time to other tasks, allowing the scheduler to run them.","images":[{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/uV5wXyZa","alt":"Basic task function","caption":"Task Function Structure"}]},
    {"title":"Creating Tasks","content":"Use `xTaskCreate()` or `xTaskCreatePinnedToCore()` to create tasks:\n\n```c\nvoid setup() {\n    xTaskCreatePinnedToCore(\n        sensorTask,       // Task function\n        \"SensorTask\",     // Task name (for debugging)\n        4096,             // Stack size in bytes\n        NULL,             // Parameter passed to task\n        1,                // Priority (higher = more important)\n        NULL,             // Task handle (optional)\n        0                 // Core to run on (0 or 1)\n    );\n    \n    xTaskCreatePinnedToCore(\n        displayTask,\n        \"DisplayTask\",\n        8192,\n        NULL,\n        2,                // Higher priority\n        NULL,\n        1                 // Different core\n    );\n}\n```\n\nThe ESP32 has two cores, so you can pin tasks to specific cores for better performance.","images":[{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/bC6dEfGh","alt":"xTaskCreate example","caption":"Creating a Task with xTaskCreate"}]},
    {"title":"Task Delays","content":"Use `vTaskDelay()` instead of `delay()` in RTOS tasks. This allows other tasks to run during the wait.\n\n```c\n// Convert milliseconds to ticks\nvTaskDelay(pdMS_TO_TICKS(100));  // 100ms delay\n\n// Direct tick count (if you know tick rate)\nvTaskDelay(100);  // 100 ticks\n```\n\nNever use blocking `delay()` in RTOS tasks - it prevents the scheduler from running other tasks."},
    {"title":"Mutexes for Shared Resources","content":"When multiple tasks access the same resource (display, serial port, shared variable), use a mutex to prevent conflicts.\n\n```c\nSemaphoreHandle_t displayMutex;\n\nvoid setup() {\n    displayMutex = xSemaphoreCreateMutex();\n}\n\nvoid displayTask(void *param) {\n    while (1) {\n        if (xSemaphoreTake(displayMutex, portMAX_DELAY)) {\n            // Safe to use display\n            tft.fillScreen(TFT_BLACK);\n            tft.drawString(\"Hello\", 10, 10);\n            \n            xSemaphoreGive(displayMutex);  // Release mutex\n        }\n        vTaskDelay(pdMS_TO_TICKS(50));\n    }\n}\n```\n\nOnly one task can hold the mutex at a time, preventing display corruption from concurrent writes.","images":[{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/iJ7kLmNo","alt":"Task with mutex","caption":"Using Mutex in a Task"},{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/pQ8rStUv","alt":"Mutex task display","caption":"Mutex Task Display Example"}]},
    {"title":"Multiple Tasks with Mutex","content":"Multiple tasks can share a resource safely using the same mutex:\n\n```c\nvoid timeTask(void *param) {\n    while (1) {\n        if (xSemaphoreTake(displayMutex, pdMS_TO_TICKS(100))) {\n            display_time();\n            xSemaphoreGive(displayMutex);\n        }\n        vTaskDelay(pdMS_TO_TICKS(1000));\n    }\n}\n\nvoid notifyTask(void *param) {\n    while (1) {\n        if (has_notification()) {\n            if (xSemaphoreTake(displayMutex, pdMS_TO_TICKS(100))) {\n                display_notification();\n                xSemaphoreGive(displayMutex);\n            }\n        }\n        vTaskDelay(pdMS_TO_TICKS(100));\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThe timeout parameter (`pdMS_TO_TICKS(100)`) prevents tasks from waiting forever if another task holds the mutex too long.","images":[{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/wX9yZaBc","alt":"Multiple tasks with mutex","caption":"Multiple Tasks Sharing a Resource"}]}
  ]')
) WHERE id = 'lesson-t-rtos';

