-- LESSON: lesson-t-static-volatile
-- Images mapped to sections:
-- page31_img1 -> "Static Variables"
-- page31_img2 -> "Volatile Variables"
-- page32_img1 -> "Combining Static and Volatile"
-- ============================================================================
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = json_set(
  json_remove(content_json, '$.images'),
  '$.sections',
  json('[
    {"title":"Introduction","content":"The `static` and `volatile` keywords modify how variables are stored and accessed. Understanding these modifiers is essential for embedded programming where you deal with interrupts, shared memory, and persistent state."},
    {"title":"Static Variables","content":"A `static` local variable retains its value between function calls, unlike regular local variables which are reinitialized each time.\n\n```c\nvoid count_calls() {\n    static int count = 0;  // Initialized once\n    count++;\n    printf(\"Called %d times\\n\", count);\n}\n\n// First call: \"Called 1 times\"\n// Second call: \"Called 2 times\"\n// Third call: \"Called 3 times\"\n```\n\nStatic variables are useful for maintaining state without using global variables, keeping the state encapsulated within the function.","images":[{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/dE0fGhIj","alt":"Static variable example","caption":"Static Variable Persists Between Calls"}]},
    {"title":"Static Functions","content":"A `static` function is only visible within its source file, preventing name conflicts with other files.\n\n```c\n// In motor.c\nstatic void configure_pwm() {\n    // Private helper function\n}\n\nvoid motor_init() {\n    configure_pwm();  // OK: same file\n}\n\n// In main.c\nconfigure_pwm();  // ERROR: not visible\n```\n\nUse static for helper functions that should not be called from other modules."},
    {"title":"Volatile Variables","content":"The `volatile` keyword tells the compiler that a variable can change unexpectedly (by hardware or interrupts). Without it, the compiler might optimize away reads, causing bugs.\n\n```c\nvolatile bool button_pressed = false;\n\nvoid IRAM_ATTR button_isr() {\n    button_pressed = true;  // Set in interrupt\n}\n\nvoid loop() {\n    if (button_pressed) {  // Compiler must read actual value\n        button_pressed = false;\n        handle_press();\n    }\n}\n```\n\nWithout `volatile`, the compiler might assume `button_pressed` never changes in `loop()` and optimize the check away.","images":[{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/kL1mNoP1","alt":"Volatile with ISR","caption":"Volatile Variable for ISR Communication"}]},
    {"title":"Combining Static and Volatile","content":"Sometimes you need both: persistence (static) and interrupt-safety (volatile).\n\n```c\nvoid check_button() {\n    static volatile uint32_t last_press = 0;\n    uint32_t now = millis();\n    \n    if (button_pin_low() && (now - last_press > 200)) {\n        last_press = now;  // Debounce timing\n        handle_press();\n    }\n}\n```\n\n`static` keeps the value between calls, `volatile` ensures the compiler does not optimize away reads if this function could be interrupted.","images":[{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/rS2tUvWx","alt":"Static volatile combined","caption":"Combining Static and Volatile"}]},
    {"title":"When to Use Each","content":"**Use `static` for:**\n- Local variables that must persist between calls\n- Functions that should be private to a file\n- Module-level variables shared within a file\n\n**Use `volatile` for:**\n- Variables modified by interrupt handlers\n- Hardware registers\n- Variables shared between RTOS tasks\n- Memory-mapped I/O\n\n**Use both for:**\n- Persistent variables accessed by interrupts\n- Debounce timers in interrupt-driven code"}
  ]')
) WHERE id = 'lesson-t-static-volatile';

