-- LESSON: lesson-t-timing
-- Images mapped to sections:
-- page33_img1 -> "Blocking Delays"
-- page33_img2 -> "Non-Blocking Timing"
-- page34_img1 -> "RTOS Task Delays"
-- page34_img2 -> "Hardware Timers"
-- page35_img1 -> "Debouncing"
-- ============================================================================
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = json_set(
  json_remove(content_json, '$.images'),
  '$.sections',
  json('[
    {"title":"Introduction to Timing","content":"Timing control is fundamental to embedded systems. You need precise timing for:\n\n- Periodic sensor readings\n- Display refresh rates\n- Communication protocols\n- User input debouncing\n- Power management\n\nDifferent approaches offer trade-offs between simplicity, precision, and CPU efficiency."},
    {"title":"Blocking Delays","content":"The simplest approach uses `delay()`, which blocks execution for a specified time.\n\n```c\nvoid loop() {\n    read_sensor();\n    delay(100);  // Wait 100ms\n    update_display();\n    delay(50);   // Wait 50ms\n}\n```\n\n**Pros:** Simple to understand and use\n**Cons:** CPU does nothing during delay; cannot respond to events; accumulates timing drift\n\nAvoid blocking delays in production code except for initialization sequences.","images":[{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/yZ3aBcDe","alt":"Blocking delay example","caption":"Blocking Delay - Simple but Inefficient"}]},
    {"title":"Non-Blocking Timing","content":"Use `millis()` to track elapsed time without blocking. This allows the CPU to do other work.\n\n```c\nuint32_t lastSensorRead = 0;\nuint32_t lastDisplayUpdate = 0;\n\nvoid loop() {\n    uint32_t now = millis();\n    \n    if (now - lastSensorRead >= 100) {\n        lastSensorRead = now;\n        read_sensor();\n    }\n    \n    if (now - lastDisplayUpdate >= 50) {\n        lastDisplayUpdate = now;\n        update_display();\n    }\n    \n    // Can do other work here\n    check_buttons();\n}\n```\n\nThis pattern enables responsive systems that handle multiple tasks concurrently.","images":[{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/fG4hIjKl","alt":"Non-blocking timing","caption":"Non-Blocking Timing with millis()"}]},
    {"title":"RTOS Task Delays","content":"In FreeRTOS, use `vTaskDelay()` instead of `delay()`. This yields CPU time to other tasks.\n\n```c\nvoid sensorTask(void *param) {\n    TickType_t lastWakeTime = xTaskGetTickCount();\n    \n    while (1) {\n        read_sensor();\n        \n        // Delay until next period (more precise)\n        vTaskDelayUntil(&lastWakeTime, pdMS_TO_TICKS(100));\n    }\n}\n```\n\n`vTaskDelayUntil()` compensates for task execution time, maintaining precise periods.","images":[{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/mN5oPqRs","alt":"RTOS task delay","caption":"RTOS Task Delay with vTaskDelay()"}]},
    {"title":"Hardware Timers","content":"For precise timing or generating signals, use hardware timers. They run independently of CPU execution.\n\n```c\nhw_timer_t *timer = NULL;\nvolatile bool timer_fired = false;\n\nvoid IRAM_ATTR onTimer() {\n    timer_fired = true;\n}\n\nvoid setup() {\n    // Configure timer: 80MHz / 80 = 1MHz (1us resolution)\n    timer = timerBegin(0, 80, true);\n    timerAttachInterrupt(timer, &onTimer, true);\n    timerAlarmWrite(timer, 1000, true);  // 1000us = 1ms\n    timerAlarmEnable(timer);\n}\n\nvoid loop() {\n    if (timer_fired) {\n        timer_fired = false;\n        // Handle timer event\n    }\n}\n```\n\nHardware timers are essential for PWM, precise measurements, and time-critical operations.","images":[{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/tU6vWxYz","alt":"Hardware timer example","caption":"Hardware Timer Interrupt"}]},
    {"title":"Debouncing","content":"Mechanical buttons bounce, causing multiple triggers. Debouncing filters out these false readings.\n\n```c\n#define DEBOUNCE_MS 50\n\nuint32_t lastDebounceTime = 0;\nbool lastButtonState = HIGH;\nbool buttonState = HIGH;\n\nvoid check_button() {\n    bool reading = digitalRead(BUTTON_PIN);\n    \n    if (reading != lastButtonState) {\n        lastDebounceTime = millis();\n    }\n    \n    if ((millis() - lastDebounceTime) > DEBOUNCE_MS) {\n        if (reading != buttonState) {\n            buttonState = reading;\n            if (buttonState == LOW) {\n                handle_press();\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    \n    lastButtonState = reading;\n}\n```\n\nThe touch screen on the T-Watch also benefits from debouncing to prevent accidental multiple taps.","images":[{"url":"https://www.genspark.ai/api/files/s/aB7cDeFg","alt":"Debounce timing","caption":"Debouncing Touch Input"}]}
  ]')
) WHERE id = 'lesson-t-timing';

